Which fruit and vegetables have the most powerful anti-inflammatory properties? The ones that are brightest in colour – its Mother Nature's way of telling us they’re rich in antioxidants, like vitamin C and E, and the carotenoids. So try boosting your intake of red/orange/yellow vegetables and fruits such as sweet potatoes, carrots, apricots and watermelon, purple foods such as berries and grapes, green foods such as watercress, sukuma and broccoli, 'seed' foods such as peas, onions and garlic, and wholegrains, fresh nuts, seeds and their oils. 






Getting it right in the gut 

Unless you’re emptying your bowels once a day, a build-up of toxic material inside the intestines is likely. When that happens, toxins can be reabsorbed back into the body. Let me paint you a picture: think of a sewer system which has nowhere to flow to, and now imagine all the build-up and leakage that would follow. That’s the same thing that happens in your gut when you don’t “go”. Quite simply, once the toxins are reabsorbed, they erupt on your skin. 

There are ample ways to increase the amount of fibre in your diet – more fresh fruits and vegetables, wholemeal bread, porridge, lentils and beans. All of these will help keep your gut regular and healthy, and in turn your skin.  



